18 March 2018

Linked Sexual Assaults in SE London

In Autumn 2017, the Met released a media appeal following a series of sexual assaults committed against females, mostly young girls in school uniform.

  • All the offences took place on a weekday
  • Offences were typically between 7am - 9am and between 3pm and 6pm
  • Nearly all the offences took place on residential streets
  • Offences spread across five London boroughs

Whilst the offences took place on foot, the offences were spread over a very large area, so the hypothesis was that perhaps the offender was taking public transport between the locations, although he could also be using a car.

The Package

Rgeoprofile https://evolve.sbcs.qmul.ac.uk/lecomber/sample-page/geographic-profiling/geographic-profiling-in-r/

Mark Stevenson, Robert Verity, Richard Nichols and Steve Le Comber

The package comprises a list of functions that must be run in order.

The output is a geoprofile overlaid on Google Maps, and a list of hitscores that can be calculated for known locations, such as train stations or home addresses of violent or sexual offenders.

Data

Your data will be comprised of two sets of coordinates:

  • First Set - the coordinates of where the crimes too place
  • Second Set - source data (optional) - the coordinates of places that may be an offender's anchor point (home address, work address, commuter stations)

The first function in the package is LoadData.

LoadData(Data=crimes, sources=stations)

Parameters for the Model

assign("sigma", 0.01, .GlobalEnv)

ModelParameters(sigma = 0.01, tau = "DEFAULT", minburnin = 100, 
                maxburnin = 1000, chains = 5, Samples = 10000)

The most important parameter is sigma. This will need to be altered to reflect the environment and the suspected mode of transport that the offender is using.

Parameters for the Map

GraphicParameters(Guardrail = 0.05, nring = 20, transp = 0.4, 
                  gridsize = 640, gridsize2 = 600, 
                  MapType = "roadmap", Location = getwd(), 
                  pointcol = "black")

These values are all dependent on how you wish your final map to look. These parameters affect format, resolution and transparancy.

Create Map

CreateMaps(PlotPrior = T)

This is the map also with the stations plotted.

points(stations, pch = 15 , col = "blue")

The next step runs the MCMC burn-in, sampling and produces diagnostic plos of convergence and autocorrelation.

RunMCMC()

ThinandAnalyse(thinning = 100)

This step thins the samples produced by the MCMC step, and uses them for analysis and for building the geoprofile.

For example, a value of 100 would keep one sample out of every 100 samples.

PlotGP(Window = "DEFAULT" , Legend = T)

This last step creates your geoprofile for you to view

The final output should look like a reverse heat map. The areas of white/pale yellow represent an area of interest.

HitScores

Reporthitscores()

The hit scores will be assigned to each location in your source data. The closer to 0 this number is, the greater probability the offender's anchor point is located there. This may aid operational search activity, and help prioritise a long list of offenders.

Whilst it was still unknown how the offender was travelling between the various locations, the rail stations of Brockley, Crofton Park and Kidbrooke had a hit score of < 0.05 so these were raised as stations where there may be CCTV available.

An offender has been arrested and charged with a number of the offences in the series. His home address is located in an area of the geoprofile with a hit score of < 0.05
